do a four-hour podcast. So, I want to touch on just a few of those. One of them from Dave was

00:04:57.799 --> 00:05:05.559
data science best practices, which is a very broad phrase, right? But he let me know, like,

00:05:05.559 --> 00:05:12.920
this is about speaking the same language, the same baseline language. And you said that even if two

00:05:13.640 --> 00:05:18.760
R devs or two Python devs are working in the same language, they're going to have different things

00:05:18.760 --> 00:05:23.320
that they do, right? That like make it harder for them to work together or for the team to

00:05:23.320 --> 00:05:29.640
work together. So, you want to be able to have sort of a unification of standards and formatting

00:05:29.640 --> 00:05:34.359
and styles and stuff. I would love to talk about that. Somebody asked Dave a question about that,

00:05:34.359 --> 00:05:41.399
or I will. There was also enterprise package development and dashboard development. Like, hey,

00:05:43.160 --> 00:05:47.320
maybe developing an internal package for your team or your org sounds like a really big lift

00:05:47.320 --> 00:05:52.440
or it sounds really nerve-wracking, but it's a really great thing. And Dave can talk about that

00:05:53.160 --> 00:05:59.559
and how it really helps with reproducibility. But the things that I really want to talk about,

00:05:59.559 --> 00:06:05.399
one of them was right-sizing development efforts. I am somebody who's going to over-optimize too

00:06:05.399 --> 00:06:10.679
early. It's a sickness. And I think that many people in data science want to do that as well.

00:06:11.320 --> 00:06:15.640
And Dave can talk about making the right amount of effort for the right projects.

00:06:16.760 --> 00:06:21.559
And then the big one, which I know a lot of people want to talk about, is working in a

00:06:21.559 --> 00:06:26.760
polyglot team and really developing, managing, facilitating a polyglot team.

00:06:28.279 --> 00:06:35.000
All of the different ways that you can work together as an R plus Python or Python plus

00:06:35.000 --> 00:06:42.200
something else team. So I'm really excited to talk about all of those. We always wait

00:06:42.200 --> 00:06:49.000
just a minute while questions roll in, but we have some questions already. And Zach had asked

00:06:49.000 --> 00:06:53.959
one that I will go ahead and ask for him because it's got an asterisk. Thanks, Zach. Which of these

00:06:53.959 --> 00:06:59.959
three pillars you mentioned is your personal favorite to work on? Ooh, that's a good one.

00:07:00.679 --> 00:07:10.119
I think learning is going to be more associated with the modeling machine learning. I think that

00:07:10.119 --> 00:07:16.679
is very fun and it's really cool to make predictions. So I think there's some immediate

00:07:16.679 --> 00:07:22.359
gratification with that. The maintenance of those long-term models that are in production

00:07:22.359 --> 00:07:28.279
may be a little bit less fun, if I'm being totally honest. And so I think the process

00:07:28.760 --> 00:07:37.480
automation is probably more what I lean on because I think any time I'm in a project like that,

00:07:37.480 --> 00:07:44.200
I find that there are way more creative opportunities on how to make something work.

00:07:45.239 --> 00:07:50.679
And I think what's really neat in that space is being able to figure out what are the right tools

00:07:50.679 --> 00:07:55.720
for the job and how do you make sure that you don't over-engineer or under-engineer

00:07:56.040 --> 00:08:02.040
a solution there. So I think I lean more towards that. I also think that being in a

00:08:02.040 --> 00:08:08.600
rather larger company, there's plenty of opportunity for this type of automation

00:08:08.600 --> 00:08:15.720
and just generalized process improvement. So I think that's actually just where I get more of

00:08:15.720 --> 00:08:22.679
my long-term satisfaction, but it's really hard to decouple all three because almost every project

00:08:22.679 --> 00:08:26.359
touches on at least two, if not all three of those pillars.

00:08:27.239 --> 00:08:31.640
Yeah, it's like a stool with three legs. It can't have less than that, fewer than that.

00:08:32.440 --> 00:08:38.440
Thank you for the question, Zach. Noor, you asked a question. I feel like Noor asks really great

00:08:38.440 --> 00:08:44.919
opening questions and so I end up wanting to throw Noor into the ring early. Noor,

00:08:44.919 --> 00:08:52.039
are you available to ask yours live? We have to go find Noor and unmute her. So hold on, Noor.

00:08:53.320 --> 00:09:02.520
Hello, here I am entering the ring center stage. That's all the wrestling terminology I know.

00:09:02.520 --> 00:09:12.679
So it's more of a broad question, but I know as a data scientist in training slash data scientist,

00:09:12.679 --> 00:09:17.000
one of the things that always comes to mind is scope creep. It's like how do you avoid it or

00:09:17.000 --> 00:09:21.159
divert it because you're like, oh, if I do this, I can save myself time. Then you're like

00:09:21.719 --> 00:09:27.320
encroaching. It's like, this is not the plan at all. So how do you avoid it or divert it,

00:09:27.320 --> 00:09:33.239
given your experience, any tips or advice? Yeah, no, that's a great question. Even the

00:09:33.239 --> 00:09:39.239
simplest of projects can have scope creep. One of the things that we've done that I think has

00:09:39.239 --> 00:09:46.119
helped with that is at the start of any bigger project, we do a lot of our planning in GitLab,

00:09:46.119 --> 00:09:53.000
but GitHub also is an option. There's a lot of project planning tools in your version control

00:09:53.000 --> 00:09:57.719
platforms. So if you're not using version control, please do it. If you are using it,

00:09:57.719 --> 00:10:03.640
please use the planning features. But one of the things that we do with that is we will actually,

00:10:03.640 --> 00:10:09.640
I have a template that we use that is basically let's state the problem. Let's state the proposed

00:10:09.640 --> 00:10:19.400
solution. Then what are the potential rabbit holes of as you're working on this project,

00:10:19.400 --> 00:10:23.960
you will likely come across this issue. Has it already been solved or is it something that we

00:10:23.960 --> 00:10:30.200
should just avoid entirely? Then finally, we'll have another section on there called no-goes.

00:10:31.080 --> 00:10:35.159
What that is is like, hey, it doesn't matter if somebody asked for this or not. This is totally

00:10:35.159 --> 00:10:41.080
out of scope of this project and we're making that known upfront. That could be like, hey,

00:10:41.080 --> 00:10:46.359
if we're doing some process automation, that's not a dashboard project. Let's make those two

00:10:46.359 --> 00:10:54.679
separate projects. Once we have refined what this storyboard looks like, we'll actually give it in

00:10:54.679 --> 00:10:58.679
front of our stakeholders so that they can say, yeah, actually, this seems like a really good

00:10:58.679 --> 00:11:05.080
plan. Or actually, what if we pivoted this? Maybe it's not answering the question that we actually

00:11:05.080 --> 00:11:12.280
want. I think a lot of those project requests that we get is if you've ever had any experience

00:11:12.280 --> 00:11:17.239
with stack overflow, you read the question and then you understand what's the question that

00:11:17.239 --> 00:11:23.479
they're actually getting at. I think by doing some project planning upfront, you're able to

00:11:23.479 --> 00:11:29.400
better craft of a solution that's like, maybe they didn't ask the question exactly how it should

00:11:29.400 --> 00:11:36.039
have been. This is a little bit of an opportunity for discovery without much overhead and also keeps

00:11:37.080 --> 00:11:42.359
you on target for what you're going for. I love it. My follow-up question is,

00:11:43.400 --> 00:11:50.039
how much of the project should be planning before any code happens? Before any code is typed?

00:11:50.760 --> 00:11:57.239
That's a tough question because I've also seen plenty of teams that spend too much time in the

00:11:57.239 --> 00:12:04.039
planning phase and not enough time in the doing phase. I don't really have a solid answer of,

00:12:04.039 --> 00:12:10.520
oh yeah, you should always spend 10% of your time planning because some projects that are

00:12:10.520 --> 00:12:15.479
small end up taking more planning and sometimes big projects are pretty self-explanatory.

00:12:16.039 --> 00:12:27.000
I would say never do a project in total isolation if you can avoid it.

00:12:27.000 --> 00:12:32.520
By just bouncing ideas off of a colleague or even your stakeholder, I think you're going to

00:12:32.520 --> 00:12:39.880
have a better product and a more well-defined scope than just jumping straight into coding.

00:12:40.440 --> 00:12:46.599
I'm not an artist, but I would also assume that I'm not going to just get some paint and just

00:12:46.599 --> 00:12:53.000
go at it. I would have a plan, I would do a sketch, a mock-up, and I think coding is very

00:12:53.000 --> 00:12:57.960
much the same. It's much easier to do planning work than it is to actually put it to code.

00:13:01.239 --> 00:13:05.400
I'm going to say more of a skeleton because you don't want to over-engineer it and there's always

00:13:06.359 --> 00:13:11.479
going to be some hang-ups or maybe some things take shorter time or more time than expected,

00:13:12.119 --> 00:13:17.719
but you should have that roadmap carved out. Now that you have that, it's more of just

00:13:19.000 --> 00:13:25.080
putting those thoughts into code rather than coding and figuring out where you're going with it.

00:13:26.280 --> 00:13:32.039
I think LLMs have probably changed this development cycle a little bit because the

00:13:32.039 --> 00:13:37.960
way that I have always worked and taught as well, before LLMs at least, and still now,

00:13:40.039 --> 00:13:45.320
write your script in pseudocode first. You plug your code in later, but write down your plan for

00:13:45.320 --> 00:13:50.119
what you're going to do in pseudocode, which is just plain language, comments and stuff,

00:13:51.239 --> 00:13:56.039
and go from there. But now with LLMs, do you feel like people are just hopping in and going,

00:13:56.039 --> 00:14:00.039
hey, LLM, make me a POC, and then they work from that like it's their blank canvas?

00:14:02.200 --> 00:14:04.840
Yeah. I don't know if there's an answer to that.

00:14:05.719 --> 00:14:14.359
No. I think that is actually a pretty phenomenal use of AI just to ideate and help lead what

00:14:14.359 --> 00:14:17.000
direction you're going in. Yeah.

00:14:17.960 --> 00:14:23.320
All right. Well, there's an anonymous question that was along the lines of this that we can

00:14:23.320 --> 00:14:29.719
tack on, and it is, do you give them what they say they want, or do you give them what they need?

00:14:30.919 --> 00:14:36.679
How do you approach that conversation? That is a very good question. I think it

00:14:36.679 --> 00:14:42.119
really depends on your prior relationship with whatever stakeholder you're working with.

00:14:43.640 --> 00:14:50.200
If you have that working relationship, obviously, you should try to actually create a solution that

00:14:50.200 --> 00:14:56.280
you think is the best solution possible. I mean, really, this feels more like a question

00:14:56.280 --> 00:15:01.880
about communication. And while I think the planning phase is important, I think it's also

00:15:01.880 --> 00:15:07.479
good to just have some check-ins throughout the process. If you're going to be working for

00:15:07.479 --> 00:15:14.919
something, say, for six weeks, it seems kind of crazy to just keep your head down, work on

00:15:14.919 --> 00:15:18.760
something, and pour your heart and soul into it, and then at the end of those six weeks realize

00:15:18.760 --> 00:15:24.440
it's either not needed anymore or what you built wasn't really answering the question at hand.

00:15:25.320 --> 00:15:32.119
And so I do think that you don't need to be over-communicative, but I think just the

00:15:32.760 --> 00:15:38.599
occasional check-in on a weekly cadence or bi-weekly cadence to say, hey, this is where

00:15:38.599 --> 00:15:43.400
we are, this is where we're heading, is really going to make sure that you're answering those

00:15:43.400 --> 00:15:48.119
questions. Are we still going in the right direction? Directionality check. All right.

00:15:48.119 --> 00:15:53.400
That was a great question, anonymous asker. Joey, I saw you had a question. Can we help

00:15:53.400 --> 00:15:59.559
Joey unmute to ask his question live? Joey Marshall, in case there's more than one Joey.

00:16:03.080 --> 00:16:08.919
Hey, Dave. Thanks for hanging out with us. My audio's on, yeah? Yeah, we hear you, Joey.

