that doesn't? And it could be anything, like health, demographics, climate. It could be

00:16:47.799 --> 00:16:53.799
geospatial data. We want to make stuff that people use, and we are still trying to innovate

00:16:53.799 --> 00:16:58.599
with official statistics. So yeah, can you just like sort of dream up? What data do you wish you

00:16:58.599 --> 00:17:07.560
had? Yeah, that's a good question that I wish I was way more prepared for. I will say one challenge

00:17:07.560 --> 00:17:16.599
that we do have is actual data access. And sometimes that we see, again, not just with any

00:17:16.599 --> 00:17:23.400
external vendor, there's not a lot of regulation about kind of that data governance layer. Are the

00:17:23.400 --> 00:17:29.239
columns consistently the same? Are the data types the same? Is this being served as an Excel file?

00:17:30.439 --> 00:17:35.719
One thing that has been incredibly helpful is when those external data sources are willing

00:17:35.719 --> 00:17:40.839
to create like an API access so that we can programmatically get that data.

00:17:41.719 --> 00:17:47.640
And so I know I'm not answering your question directly, but I am from my own,

00:17:48.760 --> 00:17:57.560
you know, perhaps own interests here, is what we've spent a lot of time on is scraping websites

00:17:57.560 --> 00:18:02.760
and downloading it and then doing a lot of data engineering internally. But it would be phenomenal

00:18:02.760 --> 00:18:13.479
if that database was like accessible outside of us doing that legwork. And so I, yeah, I don't have

00:18:13.479 --> 00:18:18.359
a great, like, feel free to put it in the chat here if anybody does have strong opinions of

00:18:18.359 --> 00:18:23.959
missing data elements. But to me, I think one of the things that would really help is just more of

00:18:23.959 --> 00:18:31.640
a unified approach to data management. Yeah, so say we all. I don't want to scrape anything. I

00:18:31.640 --> 00:18:37.239
want it all completely available via an API. I see a bunch of like nodding heads in there.

00:18:38.520 --> 00:18:45.880
Yes, thank you for the great question, Joey. All right, we had one. We had an anonymous question

00:18:45.880 --> 00:18:50.119
that was like, hey, you mentioned VS Code in our studio. Why did you not mention Positron? It's

00:18:50.119 --> 00:18:55.000
great. I love that this question says I don't work for Posit, but I've been using it for almost a

00:18:55.000 --> 00:19:03.560
year now and I love it. I will say a lot of companies are using what they have for an

00:19:03.560 --> 00:19:09.479
enterprise tool available. And so maybe they're waiting for Positron to be available. How about

00:19:09.479 --> 00:19:17.880
you guys, Dave? Yeah, we currently don't have Positron implemented, but we do have a kind of

00:19:17.880 --> 00:19:24.119
centralized resource that hosts our R studio and VS Code and Jupyter notebooks,

00:19:24.119 --> 00:19:30.599
kind of all in one unified platform. It's the equivalent of Posit Workbench. And I think that

00:19:30.599 --> 00:19:38.119
is so critical if you're a team of more than one, mainly because it's called data science for a

00:19:38.119 --> 00:19:43.880
reason. And I'm going to emphasize science. Part of science is reproducibility. And if I'm writing

00:19:43.880 --> 00:19:49.880
code and running code on my system, I would expect that you would not need to modify that

00:19:49.880 --> 00:19:56.119
code base and still be able to run that code and come to the same conclusions as what I saw.

00:19:56.119 --> 00:20:02.920
And so I think having a centralized kind of data development or data science development platform

00:20:02.920 --> 00:20:08.839
is kind of critical for any sort of collaboration, even if you're using the same language and you've

00:20:08.839 --> 00:20:15.560
already figured out how to work seamlessly as a team. Unless you're working in the exact

00:20:15.560 --> 00:20:23.000
same environment, you're going to have a lot of unneeded friction. Yeah. Can we follow this line

00:20:23.000 --> 00:20:28.680
of the data science best practices? Let's say I have a team of four devs, and they're all working

00:20:28.680 --> 00:20:33.319
in R, but they all come from different backgrounds. Maybe one of them is hardcore tidyverse. Maybe one

00:20:33.319 --> 00:20:37.959
of them is hardcore base R. Maybe they're all tidyverse, but they all write in a different

00:20:37.959 --> 00:20:45.640
style. How do you unify as a team and make it so that I can always read everybody else's code,

00:20:45.640 --> 00:20:53.479
they can always read mine? Yeah. Yeah. It's an ongoing challenge. I think the low hanging fruit

00:20:53.479 --> 00:21:00.680
there is just kind of agreeing upon a style, which seems kind of pedantic, but you'd be surprised how

00:21:00.680 --> 00:21:06.599
many hot button topics you run into when you do that. But I think the goal there is

00:21:08.760 --> 00:21:14.439
anytime that you are reading somebody else's code, you're going to have some unfamiliarity

00:21:14.439 --> 00:21:19.560
with what they're doing. Why make it more challenging with it also being an unfamiliar

00:21:19.560 --> 00:21:26.680
style or syntax or unique packages that you're not familiar with? And so, I think coming up

00:21:26.680 --> 00:21:31.959
with a familiar style guide that you all are comfortable with is a great starting point,

00:21:32.599 --> 00:21:39.000
but that's not the end of the conversation. I think it's also what are almost gold carded

